QUEUE DATA STRUCTURE
===================

Purpose : Explain the Queue data structure in a clear, structured,
          and practical manner for learning and revision.

------------------------------------------------------------

OVERVIEW
--------
A Queue is a linear data structure that follows the FIFO principle
(First In, First Out).

The element inserted first is the first one to be removed.

A real-world analogy is a line at a ticket counter.

------------------------------------------------------------
KEY CHARACTERISTICS
-------------------
- Elements are inserted at the REAR
- Elements are removed from the FRONT
- No random access
- Predictable order of processing

------------------------------------------------------------

BASIC OPERATIONS
----------------
1. Enqueue
   Inserts an element at the rear of the queue

2. Dequeue
   Removes an element from the front of the queue

3. Front
   Returns the front element without removing it

4. Rear
   Returns the last element in the queue

5. isEmpty
   Checks whether the queue is empty

6. isFull
   Checks whether the queue is full (array-based queue)

------------------------------------------------------------
QUEUE TYPES
-----------
1. Simple Queue
2. Circular Queue
3. Priority Queue
4. Deque (Double Ended Queue)

------------------------------------------------------------
QUEUE ERRORS
------------
1. Queue Overflow
   Occurs when inserting into a full queue

2. Queue Underflow
   Occurs when removing from an empty queue

------------------------------------------------------------

IMPLEMENTATION METHODS
----------------------
1. Array-Based Queue
   - Fixed size
   - Simple implementation
   - May waste space in linear queue

2. Circular Queue
   - Efficient space utilization
   - Rear connects back to front

3. Linked List-Based Queue
   - Dynamic size
   - No overflow until memory limit

------------------------------------------------------------

